\begin_layout Subsection

\size larger
Information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size larger
Limits on insurance are brought through limits on information and limits
 on enforceability.
 Misrepresentation can hide the true risks.
 Moral Hazard problem persists as well.
 For example, if high efforts are with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and no efforts with 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, then expected utility with high efforts is 
\begin_inset Formula $pU(H)+(1-p)U(L)-c$
\end_inset

 while no efforts yield 
\begin_inset Formula $qU(H)+(1-q)U(L)$
\end_inset

.
 Without insurance, the farmer puts extra effort if 
\begin_inset Formula $pU(H)+(1-p)U(L)-c>qU(H)+(1-q)U(L)$
\end_inset

.
 With insurance, if farmers with H pool their harvests and with L receive
 a compensation, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $pH+(1-p)L$
\end_inset

 assured for every farmer and since, 
\begin_inset Formula $U(pH+(1-p)L)>pU(H)+(1-p)U(L)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size larger
The question that one may ask is how much insurance can be offered without
 worsening incentives? If perfect insurance conditions fails to hold we
 consider the second best-alternative.
 
\begin_inset Formula $pX+(1-p)Y=pH+(1-p)L$
\end_inset

 for farmer's output 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 High efforts are chosen as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $pU(X)+(1-p)U(Y)-C\ge qU(X)+(1-q)U(Y)\Rightarrow(p-q)(U(X)-U(Y))\Rightarrow C$
\end_inset

.
 Under the second best scheme, individual consumption must move with individual
 income.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size larger
Considering, the reliability of a mutual insurance scheme, let us consider
 the gain from a high output individual who breaks the contract 
\begin_inset Formula $G=U(H)-U(M)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $M=pH+(1-p)L).$
\end_inset

